caption: The Statue of Liberty in Paris is a smaller replica of the famous one in New York. It is located on √éle aux Cygnes in the Seine River, near the Pont de Grenelle bridge.  Gifted to France by the French community in the U.S. in 1889, it commemorates the centennial of the French Revolution. The statue faces west toward New York as a symbol of Franco-American friendship.  Standing about 11.5 meters tall, it is one of several replicas in France and can be seen during boat tours on the Seine

Must to visit Statue of liberty and enjoy stunning views of Paris. Plenty of benches to sit and enjoy calming views of river, read a book or even a place for exercise.  This island is Not from beautiful commercial center of Paris, coffee shops, restaurants. Enjoy a new place, ile de Cygnes with Travelling Hopper in Paris.
About 800m long and narrow(around 20m?) shaped island between Bir Hakeim and Grenelle bridges. Very peaceful and quiet place. Ideal for a small walk.

A nice artificial island with a copy of the Statue of Liberty from New York. It also has some climbing walls and other workout appliances. It's fun to hang out and you get a nice view from the Eifel Tower.

This is a fantastic place to discover in Paris if you're looking for a bit of peace and quiet in the city. This narrow strip of island, 36 feet wide,  is easily accessible from several bridges including pont de Grenelle. The island is only 900 yards long and has a tree lined path down the middle with nicely shaded park benches frequently spaced.  It's a lovely place to enjoy lunch while watching the boats go by along the Seine. Joggers are plentiful,  benefitting from the shade, isolation and flat, paved pathway. I suggest starting your walk from the Grenelle bridge as you'll first encounter the one-quarter scale replica of the Statue of Liberty. The statue faces toward her big sister in New York York and is a fine sight to see in Paris! Also, as a bonus, under the bridge are various pieces of exercise equipment and rock climbing walls. Being, shaded by the bridge and with a nice breeze off the river, it was quite cool here, even on a hot day. Walking towards pont de Bir-Hakeim, you'll enjoy wonderful views of the Eiffel Tower which is just ahead. We were glad we stumbled upon this more restful piece of Paris as it allowed us to recharge a bit before a short walk brought us to the crowds at the Trocadero and the Eiffel Tower!

Do not overlook a visit to this man made island in between the 15th and 16th arrondissements. You can easily walk there in 20 mins or so after visiting the Eiffel tower/the trocadero by walking along the Seine River. It's most magical in fall, when all the trees are orange. And do not forget to go see the mini statue of liberty at the far end of it under the Pont de Grenelle. The statue was placed there 3 years after the one in New-York. It was donated by the American community in Paris. It's actually one of the 5 "molds" Eiffel made before building the full sized one. It's pretty magic to see the sunset from there.
Beautiful views of the eiffel tower and the river seine!
It is an small island of 850 meters long, it is a nice place with a nice view to be away from the crowds. I recommend this place.

An artificial island built between 1825 and 1827, its trees were planted in 1830. It is one of three islands in the Seine River within the Paris urban perimeter and the largest in length (800 m). It is bordered by the Bir Hakeim bridge upstream and the Grenelle bridge downstream, and is also crossed by the Rouelle bridge.  It can be accessed via the two bridges at the ends.  At the downstream end is a replica of the Statue of Liberty.  It is a very pleasant place to walk or rest.

A walk with trees and benches that runs between two bridges, from the Passy bridge to the Grenelle bridge; At the end of the island there is a replica of the Statue of Liberty. From this islet that surrounds the Seine River there are good views of the city with large buildings and the famous Eiffel Tower.

From this place we can observe the younger sister of the statue that France donated to New York on the occasion of the declaration of independence, the statue was specifically placed with the orientation towards the older American sister.
Take a walk along the Seine on the Isle des Swanes and admire the Statue of Liberty in Paris and the Eiffel Tower

Swan Island (√él√©e des Cygnes) is an artificial island located between the Pont de Grenelle and the Pont de Bir-Hakein, along the River Seine in the beautiful and romantic city of Paris. With a green space and sandy ground, it is a great place for walking, especially because there is a mini open-air gym right under the Pont de Grenelle. Also at this end of the island is the Statue of Liberty.

An artificial island in the heart of the Seine, a promenade in the heart of Paris, Swan Island is a place to visit for Parisians in need of greenery, passers-by wanting to sit on one of the many benches or parents came to walk their children  It was built in 1827, but its 890m long has remained intact  The place is not accessible to PMR/UFR, however the small Statue of Liberty, at the end, is. Metro 6 is right next door  Trees have been proven to help de-stress, remember, and don't miss the little divide, towards the statue, between the old and new ground
Narrow island in the middle of the Seine opposite the Quai de Grenelle. It allows you to take long walks to the Biraquaim bridge. At one end is a scaled-down reproduction of the Statue of Liberty.
